---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Permissions · Squeezy"
  description="Squeezy permission policy, shell sandboxing, checkpoints, and verification controls."
  activeDoc="/docs/permissions/"
  eyebrow="permissions"
  heading="Local power is gated by local policy."
  lead="Squeezy can read, edit, run shell commands, call compilers, fetch web content, and use MCP tools, but those capabilities go through explicit policy checks."
>
  <section class="doc-block">
    <h2>Capability classes</h2>
    <div class="doc-card-grid">
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">read</span>
        <h3>Filesystem and graph reads</h3>
        <p>Graph reads are local and read-only. Raw file reads, grep, glob, and tool-output reads are bounded and receipt-backed.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">mutate</span>
        <h3>Edits and commands</h3>
        <p>Plan mode hides mutating tools. Build mode exposes them behind the configured permission engine and optional checkpoints.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">network</span>
        <h3>Web and MCP</h3>
        <p>Web search/fetch and MCP tools are routed through capability checks, output caps, redaction, and remote-evidence labels.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">verify</span>
        <h3>Compiler and test evidence</h3>
        <p>Verification commands provide build, test, lint, and compiler evidence when the task calls for it.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-block">
    <h2>Sandbox note</h2>
    <p>macOS and Linux can use stronger filesystem and network sandboxing. On Windows, shell sandboxing is Job-Object-only and filesystem/network isolation degrades to best-effort-unavailable; required mode denies before spawn.</p>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
